# Resume Builder Windsurf Rules

## Core Direction

- Build this as a conventional Rails 8, server-rendered Resume Builder.
- Favor Rails-first, HTML-first solutions that fit the current app shape.
- Keep code clear, small, DRY, SOLID, and easy to review.
- Prefer modern, stable approaches over extra abstraction or dependency weight.

## Architecture

- Keep controllers centered on HTTP concerns.
- Keep business workflows in services, domain rules in models and policies, reusable presentation in components, and async work in jobs.
- Extend existing namespaces and flows instead of creating parallel patterns.

## Rails Best Practices

- Follow Rails conventions, project linting rules, and the existing repo style.
- Favor strong parameters, explicit validations, transactions, and eager loading where they improve correctness and performance.
- Prefer Active Record relations over raw SQL unless a query clearly needs otherwise.
- Preserve established HTML and progressive enhancement flows when both already exist.
- Keep persisted JSON and JSONB payloads consistent, with string keys for stored data.

## Resume Builder Direction

- Keep the app HTML-first; add JSON only when clearly needed and keep it aligned with current patterns.
- Keep preview and PDF output aligned through shared rendering and export paths.
- Follow established authentication, authorization, and background-work conventions.
- Keep async tasks small and push complex workflows toward services.

## Comments, Docs, and Tests

- Add high-signal comments for non-obvious logic, workflows, data shapes, and tradeoffs.
- Keep comments and docs concise, accurate, and close to the feature.
- Update documentation and tests whenever behavior, setup, or workflows change.
- Match test coverage to the layer being changed and avoid testing implementation details.

## Maintenance and Reviews

- Look for nearby bugs, edge cases, and safe cleanup opportunities while working.
- Fold in small, low-risk improvements when they clearly help the feature or codebase.
- Record deferred issues, risks, and future enhancements in summaries or docs.
- Self-review for correctness, authorization, performance, comments, docs, and tests before considering work done.

## Commits and Quality

- Keep changes focused and ready for small, logical commits.
- When committing, favor clear messages that explain intent and scope.
- Before pushing, verify relevant tests, linting, migrations, and documentation updates.
- Avoid dead code, clutter, broken flows, and speculative refactors.

## Security and Reliability

- Never hardcode secrets, credentials, or API keys.
- Validate and sanitize input and rely on standard Rails protections against SQL injection, XSS, and CSRF.
- Keep side effects explicit, move heavy work off the request path when reasonable, and prefer idempotent background behavior where practical.
- Surface risky areas, rollback concerns, and practical follow-up recommendations.

## Windsurf Output

- Match existing structure, naming, and formatting.
- Prefer production-ready Rails solutions over quick hacks.
- Include authorization, error handling, comments, tests, and docs when the change warrants them.
- Call out issues outside the immediate task with a practical recommendation.
